## Coding Rules — Follow These Always

### 1. NEVER hardcode colors, spacing, or font sizes
```
# WRONG:
backgroundColor: "#7C3AED"
fontSize: 16
padding: 12

# CORRECT:
import { THEME } from "../constants/theme"
backgroundColor: THEME.colors.primary
fontSize: THEME.fontSize.md
padding: THEME.spacing.md
```

### 2. File naming conventions
- Screen files: lowercase with hyphens (add-item.tsx)
- Component files: PascalCase (OutfitCard.tsx)
- Helper files: camelCase (supabase.ts)

### 3. TypeScript — always use types
```
# WRONG:
const [items, setItems] = useState([])

# CORRECT:
interface WardrobeItem { id: string; photo_url: string; clothing_type: string }
const [items, setItems] = useState<WardrobeItem[]>([])
```

### 4. Always handle loading and error states
Every data fetch must have:
- A loading state (show ActivityIndicator)
- An error state (show friendly message, not a crash)
- An empty state (show helpful message when no data)

### 5. Supabase patterns
```typescript
# Always check for errors:
const { data, error } = await supabase.from("table").select("*")
if (error) throw new Error(error.message)

# Always filter by user_id:
.eq("user_id", user.id)
```

### 6. API calls always go through lib/api.ts
Never call the backend URL directly from screens.
Always add new functions to lib/api.ts and import them.

### 7. Occasions list
Always import from constants/occasions.ts:
```
import { OCCASIONS } from "../constants/occasions"
```
Never hardcode occasion strings like "casual" in components.

## Supabase Database Schema

### profiles
- id (uuid, references auth.users)
- email (text)
- skin_tone (text: "fair" | "medium" | "tan" | "dark")
- body_type (text: "slim" | "average" | "athletic" | "broad")
- created_at (timestamp)

### wardrobe_items
- id (uuid, primary key)
- user_id (uuid, references profiles.id)
- photo_url (text, Cloudinary URL)
- clothing_type (text: "shirt" | "trousers" | "shoes" | "jacket" | "shorts" | "dress" | "accessory")
- colors (text[], array of hex codes like ["#1a2b3c"])
- formality (text: "casual" | "smart-casual" | "formal")
- pattern (text: "plain" | "striped" | "checked" | "printed")
- season (text: "all" | "summer" | "winter")
- tags (text[], extra tags)
- created_at (timestamp)

### outfit_suggestions
- id (uuid)
- user_id (uuid)
- occasion (text)
- item_ids (uuid[], IDs of wardrobe_items in this outfit)
- feedback (text: "liked" | "disliked" | null)
- weather_temp (integer)
- created_at (timestamp)

## Backend (StyleGuru-Backend) Structure
```
StyleGuru-Backend/
├── services/
│   ├── cloudinary_service.py  Upload photos
│   ├── vision.py              Google Vision analysis
│   └── outfits.py             Claude outfit suggestions
├── main.py                    FastAPI server
├── requirements.txt
├── Procfile
└── .env                       SECRET keys (never commit this)
```

## Backend API Endpoints
- GET  /                  Health check
- POST /analyze-item      Upload + analyze a clothing photo
- POST /suggest-outfits   Get 3 outfit combinations from wardrobe

## The 10 Occasions
casual, office, party, wedding, outdoor, beach, date, gym, temple, interview

Note: "temple" is for Sri Lankan cultural/religious events.
For temple occasion: suggest modest clothing, light/muted colors (white, cream, pastel),
avoid black/red/very bright colors, covered shoulders, no shorts.

## Environment Variables

### StyleGuru React Native (.env)
```
EXPO_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_URL=https://xxxx.supabase.co
EXPO_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_ANON_KEY=eyJhbGc...
EXPO_PUBLIC_API_URL=https://styleguru-backend-xxxx.onrender.com
EXPO_PUBLIC_WEATHER_KEY=your-openweathermap-key
```

### StyleGuru-Backend (.env) — SECRET, never commit
```
GOOGLE_VISION_KEY=your-google-vision-key
ANTHROPIC_API_KEY=sk-ant-your-key
CLOUDINARY_URL=cloudinary://API_KEY:API_SECRET@CLOUD_NAME
```

## Common mistakes to avoid
- Do NOT hardcode colors — always use THEME
- Do NOT put API keys in React Native code — keys stay in backend .env
- Do NOT skip loading states — every API call needs one
- Do NOT use inline styles for repeated values — use THEME
- Do NOT call the backend directly from screens — use lib/api.ts
- Do NOT commit .env files to GitHub — they are in .gitignore
- Do NOT use WidthType.PERCENTAGE in any tables — always DXA
- Do NOT skip error handling — wrap every API call in try/catch

## How outfit suggestions work
1. Frontend fetches user's full wardrobe from Supabase
2. Frontend calls POST /suggest-outfits with {wardrobe, occasion, weather}
3. Backend (outfits.py) formats wardrobe as readable text list
4. Backend sends the list + occasion + weather to Claude API
5. Claude returns 3 outfit combinations as JSON with item_ids + explanation
6. Frontend looks up each item_id in the wardrobe array
7. Frontend shows the actual photos of those items together as an outfit card

## How clothing analysis works
1. User photographs a clothing item in add-item.tsx
2. Frontend calls POST /analyze-item with the photo file
3. Backend uploads photo to Cloudinary → gets permanent URL
4. Backend sends URL to Google Vision API
5. Google Vision returns labels (clothing type) + colors + properties
6. Backend maps labels to: clothing_type, colors, formality, pattern
7. Backend returns all of this + the Cloudinary URL to the frontend
8. Frontend saves the full item to Supabase wardrobe_items table
9. Item appears in the user's wardrobe grid immediately

## Sri Lankan cultural context
- Include "Temple / Poya" as a distinct occasion (not just "formal")
- Colombo weather is 27-33°C year round — all suggestions assume tropical heat
- Prefer light, breathable fabric suggestions in AI prompts
- South Asian skin tones are underrepresented in global fashion datasets
  — Claude's outfit suggestions should be color-aware for all skin tones
- Sri Lankan weddings: white is acceptable (unlike some other Asian cultures)
- Traditional occasions may involve sarong — treat as valid clothing item
